{"url": "https://www.reddit.com/r/learnprogramming/comments/9b91n3/cim_new_to_thisplease_help_me/", "text": "I am trying to print a and b from the read\\_data() function in the main() function,but i don't know how.\n\n    #include <iostream>\n    using namespace std;\n    \n    void read_data()\n    {\n    \tint a, b;\n    \tcout << \"Enter account code: \" << endl;\n    \tcin >> a;\n    \tcout << \"Enter balance: \";\n    \tcin >> b;\n    }\n    \n    int main()\n    {\n    \tread_data();\n    \tcout << a << endl;\n    \tcout << b << endl;\n        cout << \"\\n\";\n    \tsystem(\"pause\");\n    }\n\n&#x200B;", "score": 3, "comments": [{"body": "As you currently have it, the variables `a` and `b` solely exist in `read_data`. This is called *variable scope*.\n\nSince the variables don't exist outside `read_data` it is impossible to print them.\n\nYou need to change the scope of the variables or pass them by reference, as /u/fvalle1 stated.", "id": "e516llq", "replies": [{"body": "Thank you very much!", "id": "e516pyw", "replies": []}]}, {"body": "Use variable passed by reference, something like:\n\nvoid read(int &a, int &b){\n\ncin>>a;\ncin>>b;\n\n}\n\nint main(){\n\nInt a, b;\n\nread(a,b);\n\ncout<<a<<b;\n\n}", "id": "e516hs0", "replies": [{"body": "Thank you very much!", "id": "e516pnl", "replies": []}]}, {"body": "And char statements can be passed through functions the same way?", "id": "e516roh", "replies": [{"body": "Any type can be passed by reference", "id": "e517elg", "replies": [{"body": "Thank you!", "id": "e517fz7", "replies": []}]}]}], "title": "[C++]I'm new to this,please help me!"}